## {{ rule.title }}

[26 U.S.C. § 6038D](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/6038D) and [26 CFR § 1.6038D-2](https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/26/1.6038D-2) require U.S. individuals holding "specified foreign financial assets" above filing-status- and residency-dependent thresholds to file [Form 8938](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-8938) ("Statement of Specified Foreign Financial Assets") with the income tax return. [31 U.S.C. § 5314](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/31/5314) and [31 CFR § 1010.350](https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/31/1010.350) require U.S. persons whose aggregate foreign financial accounts exceed $10,000 at any point during the year to file [FinCEN Form 114 (FBAR)](https://bsaefiling.fincen.treas.gov/) — separately, with FinCEN, NOT with the IRS.

These two regimes are determinations only — they do NOT change tax owed. The engine surfaces REQUIRED / NOT REQUIRED for each regime so the user can confirm whether to attach Form 8938 to Form 1040 and/or file FBAR with FinCEN.

